<stream type="das-basic-stream" version="3.0" >
<properties>
  <p name="info">
  This example stream exists to make a concrete point. The base das3 codec
  truly does not understand what goes on inside an extension codec and 
  doesn't pretend to. In this stream we suppose that someone has made a
  das2C plugin that just gives the pixel count of images that flow through
  the system and does not expand the actual pixel values into a 2-D grid
  per image.
  </p>
</properties>
</stream>
|Hx|01|1862|
<dataset name="thumb" rank="1" index="*">
  <!--
    The producer of this stream probably pulls the time code from the image
    set, placing it here in a separate coordinate field. Converting an embedded
    blob into multiple variables is not supported by the extension plugin
    architecture, though a bespoke reader could produce a valid stream from
    image sets alone if desired.
  -->
  <coord physDim="time" name="time" axis="t">
    <scalar use="center" semantic="datetime" storage="struct" index="*" units="UTC">
      <packet numItems="1" itemBytes="24" encoding="utf8" fill="0001-01-01T00:00:00.000000" />
    </scalar>
  </coord>
  <data physDim="count" name="img_size">
    <!-- 
      Note the index below: We are telling the codec extension that we're 
      expecting a single value (no extent in `j` or `k`).  If it can't
      honor that contract then it has to return an error during setup or
      at parse time.
    -->
    <scalar use="center" storage="uint" semantic="integer" index="*" units="">
      <properties>
        <!-- 
        The variable's declared property list may be extended by the plugin
        at instantiation time.  Properties placed here will override any 
        provided by the extension.
        -->
        <p name="source">Victor's observations</p>
      </properties>
      <!--
      This packet declares a MIME type, which means something other then
      the routines built into das2C must decode the payload into the
      semantic, storage and array shape listed above.  A conformant reader
      without access to a jpeg decoder would likely throw an error upon
      reading this header. Note that if 'storage' is absent the extension
      is free to pick the value type.
      -->
      <packet numItems="1" itemBytes="*" encoding="base64" mime="image/jpeg" />
    </scalar>
  </data>
</dataset>
